	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Just a couple comments:<BR>
<BR>
1. I realize that not everybody has the resources to upgrade continually, but to expect a major software enterprise like Verant to support backwards-compatibility for obsolete, poorly written, badly designed operating systems like Windows95 is just wishful thinking.  Backwards compatibility is why Win2k and WinXP are so damned big right now.  They could get those operating systems down to 100megs if they didn't have to support legacy hardware from the dawn of the Internet Age.  If you can afford to pay for 2 accounts every month, it shouldn't be too hard to scrape up the $50-60USD to buy a copy of Win98Upgrade.<BR>
<BR>
2. About the game being unplayable.  I followed the instructions on the eqlive.station.sony.com tech support page. As a result, after waiting till a non-peak time to start the patch, I patched in less than 2 hrs and the game with SoL runs fine.  My other account, for which I did not purchase SoL as it is primarily a mule, also runs fine, on a pitiful Celeron466 w/128mb of ram and a 16mb PCI 3d card. Just make sure all the luclin textures are TURNED OFF in your eqclient.ini file. Instructions for how to do this are on the page at the link listed above.<BR>
<BR>
3.  Legal action?  As so many have said, if you want to try and force a legal issue, go right ahead. If you think Verant/Sony is going to pay you any more than your $40 for the software and maybe a month or two of subscription, you're sadly mistaken.  Even in America - Land of The Lawsuit, the only winners are the lawyers.  You can bet your bootie that when your lawyer isn't in earshot, he's laughing his a$$ off at someone who'd try and sue Sony for $60-70USD, but I'm sure he'll thank you for buying him yet another BMW.<BR>
<BR>
4. Finally, all this talk about being &quot;forced&quot; to upgrade.  Nobody at Verant is holding a gun to your head and saying &quot;PLAY OUR FUGGING GAME OR WE WILL BLOW YOUR HEAD OFF&quot;.  Welcome to America, Land of Free Choice. You don't like it? Cancel your subscription, write a nasty letter, and move on to another game.  When you subscribe to EverQuest, you are not buying anything except the ability to play in THEIR environment, on THEIR hardware, using (for the most part) THEIR bandwidth.  You are in effect renting server time. That's all.  At no point will you ever see in the EULA that they are responsible for providing you with a fun time. They supply the world, you supply the fun. If that doesn't work for you, see the beginning of this paragraph: cancel, move on.<BR>
<BR>
I have a lot of sympathy for Bill Sykes, who is very frustrated in that he can't spend time in EQ with his son because of these issues.  But to blame them entirely on Verant is simplistic and unrealistic.  The software gaming industry will not and CAN NOT wait for all the Bill Sykes' in the world to upgrade.  For every Bill Sykes that plays EQ, there are probably 100 other people who WANTED and DEMANDED this type of upgrade from Verant.  This is democracy.  The majority spoke, the minority hurts. It's not perfect, but it's better than what they have in a lot of other countries.  <BR>
<BR>
Bill, I hope you manage to get your software and hardware issues worked out, and we'll see you in EQ soon.  If not, I hope you are able to find another activity to spend with your son.  <BR>
<BR>
Aahzmandius Skeevesbane<BR>
Whuppin' Evil's Ass for 55 Seasons<BR>
Nemesys Guild - Luclin Server<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
