	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				It's nice to hide beneath anonimity isn't it Anti? <BR>
<BR>
While there may be better scenerio analogies to use, I think that mine effectively illustrates the situation at hand. When you purchase EQ, you are purchasing property rights. You are then required to purchase time online which is the &quot;gas&quot; to make EQ work. The software does you no good if the time isn't purchased as a car will not run if it does not have fuel. Had my car's manufacturer imposed an ordeal that would only allow their cars to run on Supreme grade gasoline after I had purchased it, what choice would I have but to obey it? My purchase would do me no good not to invest in the extra steps. When most people purchased EQ, they believed that it would be a game that they would dedicate their time to. Noone would still be playing if they thought that Verant would close shop anytime soon. On the flip side, not many people would continue to play if EQ won't offer equal or better gameplay that its predecessors will offer. EQ is the standard for similar games and to this day still hands down has an edge on the competition. Verant did not do this to screw over you or anybody else. What self serving goal would that accomplish? They don't make a dime if you have to buy a new OS, video card or RAM. Without the new specs to peak intrest from older players and appeal to new ones, EQ would run flat and less people would be apt to play. I used the Nintendo/Playstation analogy to show you what gamers turn to. When Nintendo first came out, it was the THING to have for any kid. I had to wait 3 weeks on a waiting list just to rent Super Mario Bros. 3 from a local video store. 15 years after the release of Nintendo, a video store carrying an original Nintendo game would be a challenge to find. These days, we have X-box and Playstation written on our dollar bills. Could Nintendo release games for their original system that could effectively compete with today's standards? No, they couldn't. Nintendo systems were 8-bit systems. An N64 system is a 64-bit system, hence the name, and had gameplay more appealing at the time. The &quot;bit&quot; part of the description refers to the visuals and sound of a game. In order to utilize these enhancements, a more powerful system is necessary. EQ has the disadvantage of being a set world only able to grow with expansions. Take the Ultima series for example. You could play the original game in Win 3x or DOS with 8MB of RAM. The latest release requires at least Win 95 with 64 MB of RAM. The point is that games like Ultima are sold as seperate episodes and change to compete with the market thus upping system requirements. Buying Ultima 5 didn't expand on Ultima 4 as an expansion does for EQ. It is a seperate entity therefore not binding itself with the same specs as its previous edition. Is it really too much to ask people to upgrade their OS to play an enhanced game? Certainly not. Almost any game released today will require a minimum of Windows 98 to run. (Take newer Myst games for instance). If anything, the upgrade will help out in the long run overall. Noone is entitiled to owning the expansion. It is a luxary, not a requirement so an arguement can't be made that you will HAVE to purchase additional Ram/video periphials. If you could run EQ before, upgrading to Win 98 will not prove any differently with the new patches. (Of course also downloading Directx 8.1) I can understand the dissapointment but can't comprehend why some are presenting this as if it was an &quot;oh, by the way&quot; type of change. 6 months this information has been available and several resources could have been utilized as I said in my previuos post. It is hard to offer much sympathy for people so concerned on logging in for a camp instead of taking time to research the requirements. Every expansion since the relase has had stronger requirements. Why would this one be any different?<BR>
<BR>
Ossian Cumhaill<BR>
Bard of Sol Ro<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

