	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				In 1999 I bought a Silver Mitsubishi Eclipse Spyder brand new from a local dealership. At the time, that was my prized possesion as I had always wanted one. In 2000, they changed the body style of the car to a more appealing look. Am I entitled to sue the manufacteror for &quot;making me&quot; spend $15,000 on a car that now considered an older body style because I wasn't &quot;informed&quot; that a new look would be available the following year? No, I can't. No where in my contract did it state that the body style I purchased would not be changed as time passes. I can pony up another $15,000 for a newer one if I so choose to. I can take my car to a body shop and have it modified to mirror the new body style if I am so inclined. I can also sell my car and purchase one from a different manufacturer to suit my immediate personal tastes. What I can't do is expect to be compensated for lack of research of information on my part before deciding to purchase the car. All 3 of these options are also available for you, the consumer, with regards to Everquest. You may upgrade your OS, purchase a more EQ friendly system/upgrade your current one, or simply choose to play a game that more suits your immediate situation. No one ever said that life is fair.<BR>
<BR>
Do I have a case if my two year old car's alternator goes out to no fault of my own? No, it is my responsibility to take care of all repairs and modifications once I purchase the car from the dealership unless it is covered by an expressed warranty. Verant offers no such warranty anywhere. It does, however, explicitely state in the User Agreement that EQ is an envolving community and they reserve the right to modify at will. If tomorrow they decided to close shop, no refund would be offered for software and your time and efforts are lost. There is a reason you have to accept the agreement before you can log on to the game everytime: You are agreeing to play by their rules and they are in return offering you the right to play. More than fair warning was given on the new system requirements. You have been provided a phone number to call Verant, a website for resources and several patch messages for more information. There is even an option to chat with a GM or fellow players prior to logging on to your desired server. If you are a follower of EQ, certainly you knew that their would be an enhanced graphics engine and a new race/world to play with this new expansion. Once you buy the software and sign up for service, it is YOUR responsibility to make sure that your system will be compatible. When I first brought Everquest home, I had to purchase a 3D accelerator card just to log on. I invested in more RAM just to be cautious. Most of you have been in the game long enough to know how it works. What was the first thing you did on December 3rd? For the lot of you, it was wake up early, call in sick/stay home from school and jet to your local retail store to be the first on your block to get the new expansion. Had you researched before hand, you would have been prepared for the changes. I feel that some of you expected Verant to give you a phone call or knock on your door to give you a heads up. What more could they do to inform you before hand?<BR>
<BR>
No false advertising claims can be made against Verant. When EQ/Kunark/Velious came out, the specs listed were valid at the time just as my car was the &quot;new&quot; body style when I bought it. As time passes, so will technology. How many of you would have purchased EQ if the specs used to be what they are today?  Find a recent game that is equally graphic and internet intensive and compare the specs. 99.9% will require a minimum of Windows 98. This is not to mention the processor/ram/video gard required for smoother game play. A Pentium II was an &quot;uber&quot; machine a few years back and now it is a typewriter in todays standards. Windows is no exception. As more and more computer games come out, the requirements will gradually become more sophisticated to accomidate a gamer's desires. Would you rather play on a Nintendo or a Playstation? Would you be more likely to pop quarters into a Super Mario Bros. machine or Mortal Kombat? With these desires come compromises. A remote control is a conveinent way to watch TV with little effort of channel surfing. It does you no good if it has no batteries to power it. Without the new specs, the game cannot improve and people will take their intrest and money elsewhere. Log onto Anarchy Online sometime...I'm sure you will find a few disgruntled former EQers.<BR>
<BR>
EQ is not a casual gamer's game. While some may choose to view it as such, the mere fact time invested to level shows it to be very time consuming. Pre-Kunark, one of the only effeciant ways to level up was to kill guards in Freeport. Post Kunark, Several new dungeons and zones were added to accomodate those who had reached the previous level cap of 50. When the bar was raised to 60, high level players had the opportunity to &quot;enjoy&quot; the hunt again. With the Velious and SOL expansions, there are new zones and areas to explore. If Everquest were just about leveling up to the top, people would tire of it quickly. The fact that the world continues to expand intrigues intrest and keeps Verant in business. If no expansions were added and gameplay was kept the same, people would seek out another place to spend their money. <BR>
<BR>
I can empathize with the dissapointment that some of you have and wish I could help ease the blow. Everquest is a continuously expanding game and an investment of both time and money. History has shown this from the beginning. (28k baud modem to 56k, 2x cd rom to 16x, 64 MB of ram to 128 MB, etc.) While the future of EQ is uncertain, rest assured that the system requirements will again change to accomodate future gameplay and technology. If you are not willing to change with the times, then this is your opportunity to re-evaluate the importance of this game in your life. As they say on Wall Street you have to &quot;cut your losses while you can.&quot; The game is shipped. People are playing. Patches are downloading. Where can you go from here?<BR>
<BR>
The slogan speaks for itself: &quot;You're in our world now.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Flame me as you will...<BR>
<BR>
Ossian Cumhaill<BR>
Bard of the Sol Ro Server
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
